[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \D9, which looks like top of a sequence, so West likely holds the \DKJ behind dummy's \DA5 — but treat the placement as a read, not a certainty. Win the \DA, then draw two rounds of trump and stop, keeping a trump in dummy as a re-entry and a ruffing threat. Now cash my \DQ and ruff dummy's last diamond in hand to strip diamonds, then cash both top hearts and exit a third heart. Whoever wins is out of safe red exits and must either lead a club up to \CAJT9 or concede a ruff-and-discard — either way the \CQ guess never comes up.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Ten tricks: five trumps, the two top clubs plus two more after the endplay, and the diamond ace. The strip-and-throw-in turned a 50-50 club finesse into a sure thing — the defender did the work for me. Nicely judged to keep that trump entry instead of drawing them all.}
